		<item>
		<title>4 Super-Actionable Google Ads Tips to Try Right Now</title>
		<link>https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2016/07/18/actionable-adwords-tips</link>
					<comments>https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2016/07/18/actionable-adwords-tips#respond</comments>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Erin Sagin]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Mon, 11 Jul 2016 05:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Paid Search Marketing]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2016/07/11/actionable-adwords-tips/</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[<p>Looking for some fresh strategies to implement in your AdWords account? Here are 4 super-actionable AdWords tips and techniques that deliver proven results!</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2016/07/18/actionable-adwords-tips">4 Super-Actionable Google Ads Tips to Try Right Now</a> appeared first on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com">WordStream</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="9a7bff2f-0709-49fb-93b9-417b4364f282" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/adwords-tips-title.jpg" alt="adwords tips title image" width="696" height="389" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p>This month, I‚Äôve been working hand-in-hand with Google account managers to review and assess a group of accounts, ultimately coming up with our top three most impactful recommendations for each account. During these conversations, I‚Äôve learned a few new Google Ads (formerly known as AdWords)¬†tips and techniques and different approaches to the ‚Äúold faithfuls‚Äù we‚Äôve been using here at WordStream for years.</p>
<p>Looking for some fresh strategies to implement in your Google Ads¬†account? Here are four super-actionable Google Ads¬†tips that I‚Äôll definitely be trying in the next few weeks!</p>
<h2>Google Ads¬†Tip #1: Combine Branded Terms with Modified Broad Keywords</h2>
<p>The secret to lowering your CPCs and simultaneously boosting your ad rank lies in Google‚Äôs mystery metric‚Äî<a href="/quality-score">Quality Score</a>. Savvy advertisers are perpetually tweaking their accounts in pursuit of those coveted 10‚Äôs, but achieving high scores isn‚Äôt an easy feat. In fact, it seems as though the only keywords that consistently score 7-10‚Äôs are branded terms.</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="686a71d1-3018-4659-921d-ef65aa312288" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/adwords-tips-quality-score.jpg" alt="quality score" width="542" height="153" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p><strong>¬†</strong>Branded terms are a slam dunk for <a href="/blog/ws/2013/03/19/why-bid-on-branded-terms-ppc">many reasons</a>. Firstly, it‚Äôs easy to create super-relevant ads and landing pages for these keywords, as your brand should appear regularly throughout your ad copy and website. Even better, the people who are searching your branded terms likely have strong intent; they know exactly what company they‚Äôre looking for so they‚Äôre apt to click on your ads and have high engagement rates on your website.</p>
<p>While these keywords maybe be the holy grail for high Quality Scores, you certainly don‚Äôt want to limit your ad visibility to people who already know of and are looking for your brand. That said, you <em>can</em> leverage the power of these branded keywords to impact the Quality Scores of non-branded terms.</p>
<p>Here‚Äôs how the hack works ‚Äì create keywords that are a combination of branded and non-branded terms. Set the non-branded term to modified broad (using + signs), but leave the branded term on broad. Using this technique will allow your ads to show when people search combinations of your non-branded terms‚Äîyour branded terms do not have to be present.</p>
<p>So, for example, let‚Äôs say that your branded term is Havaianas and your non-branded terms are neon flip flops. You‚Äôd add the keyword as <em>havaianas +neon +flip +flops</em>, and the ad would be eligible to show for search queries that include the words <em>neon, flip </em>and<em> flops.</em></p>
<p>Why does this technique yield high Quality Scores? Remember, Google calculates your scores based on exact matches to your keyword term. Because the ‚Äúofficial‚Äù keyword technically includes your branded terms, it‚Äôs likely to yield a stellar Quality Score.</p>
<h2>Google Ads¬†Tip #2: Take Advantage of Location-Based Bid Modifiers</h2>
<p>One of the best ways to fine tune your Google Ads¬†account is to identify what‚Äôs working and amplify it (or promote your ‚Äúunicorns‚Äù‚Äîin Larry Kim speak). One route to do this is through location-based bid modifiers.</p>
<p>Far too many advertisers set their targeting to reflect the areas where their products are sold and neglect to revisit these settings. The problem is, not all geographic locations yield the same performance. For example, if you sell hunting equipment, there‚Äôs a good chance that you‚Äôll see more conversions coming from searchers in rural areas where hunting is a popular sport than those in heavily populated urban centers.</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="d99b2c72-f6f5-48f0-9730-5c3dda9aa811" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/adwords-tips-search-query-report.jpg" alt="search query report" width="645" height="230" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p>Rather than guesstimating which regions are the most valuable for your business, head to the Dimensions Tab and set your view to Geographic. This will produce a sortable report that breaks down your performance metrics by country, region, metro area, city and ‚Äúmost specific location.‚Äù Organize by conversions to understand the regions that are bringing in the most sales for your business.</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="eb450531-cc4f-476e-9f14-4514743833dd" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/adwords-tips-bid-adjustment.jpg" alt="mobile bid adjustment" width="511" height="274" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p>Once you‚Äôve identified your most valuable locations, revisit your location targeting settings and set a positive bid adjustment for each of these locations. Higher bids will help you to attain <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2019/05/16/gallery-ads">better visibility</a> for searchers located in (or searching for products within) your top locations, ushering in even more conversions.</p>
<h2>Google Ads Tip #3: Reach Beyond Your Current Language Settings</h2>
<p>According to a 2013 <a href="http://cis.org/record-one-in-five-us-residents-speaks-language-other-than-english-at-home">study</a> by the Center for Immigration Studies, one in five US residents speaks a language other than English in their household. However, just because their preferred language isn‚Äôt English does not mean that the vast majority of these people don‚Äôt <em>also</em> speak English.</p>
<p>Remember, AdWords bases its language targeting settings on a Google user‚Äôs interface language. Users can edit this setting to ensure that Google provides results in their selected language, regardless of their physical location.</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="f7e3e138-a4c2-4e64-a768-e904c3355908" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/adwords-tips-bilingual.jpg" alt="adwords settings bilingual" width="473" height="296" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p>As you can see, when I change my preferred language settings to Spanish, I‚Äôm only served ads that are targeted to Spanish speakers, despite the fact that I am logged into the US version of Google.com.</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="7fb09c0a-0f30-4425-98b9-32d16d139f92" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/adwords-tips-spanish-search.jpg" alt="search spanish profile" width="637" height="200" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p>As you can imagine, many of these bilingual Americans set their first language as their primary language on Google, effectively eliminating ads from any companies who do not include <a href="/blog/ws/2013/09/26/language-targeting-adwords">Spanish-language targeting</a> in their Google Ads campaigns. This is a huge source of missed opportunity for US-based advertisers who absolutely should be advertising to the bilingual consumer-base.</p>
<p>It may sound like a headache to expand your advertising efforts to a completely new market, but it‚Äôs actually quite simple. First, identify which languages are most prominent in your target regions.</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="243d0a38-3d7b-4c7b-b053-ea3194e6afcf" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/adwords-tips-language-map.jpg" alt="map for most commonly spoken language other than english" width="637" height="420" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p class="text-align-center"><em>Source: </em><a href="http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/culturebox/2014/05/language_map_what_s_the_most_popular_language_in_your_state.html"><em>Slate.com</em></a></p>
<p>Then, adjust your language targeting settings to include this new audience.</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="975445cd-2d04-4b1d-91e3-5dd213fffa02" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/adwords-tips-language-settings.jpg" alt="language settings adwords" width="640" height="529" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p>That‚Äôs it! There‚Äôs no need to add non-English keywords, ads or landing pages. It almost feels too good to be true, right?</p>
<p>Here‚Äôs why this trick works‚Äîif your website doesn‚Äôt translate seamlessly or your sales reps aren‚Äôt trained to support multiple languages, you really shouldn‚Äôt risk going ‚Äúwhole hog‚Äù and <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2019/08/09/google-ads-campaign">creating campaigns</a> specifically for non-English speakers. This could actually do more harm than good, as this campaign would likely garner plenty of impressions and clicks, but fewer conversions. Instead, this trick truly helps you to connect with a bilingual audience; people who are using a non-English browser but will still understand and respond to ads written in English.</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="7b2f5f9d-8ead-4953-aeef-ac4e222b1b47" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/adwords-tips-grubhub.jpg" alt="grubhub bilingual ad example" width="633" height="293" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p>As you can see in the example above, GrubHub has adopted this strategy perfectly. This is clearly a bilingual searcher (her Google profile is set to Spanish, but she is searching in English) and GrubHub‚Äôs English ad should suit her just fine!</p>
<h2>Google Ads Tip #4: Salvage Dying Ad Groups with RLSA</h2>
<p>Ever have an ad group that you feel <em>really</em> good about but it just isn‚Äôt pulling through with strong results? It‚Äôs hard to hit the pause button when your gut tells you that these keywords hold unseen potential. It‚Äôs also hard to justify running keywords that aren‚Äôt yielding many clicks.</p>
<p>Rather than pulling the plug completely, try resurrecting your ad group using <a href="/blog/ws/2016/06/08/rlsa">Remarketing Lists for Search Ads (RLSA)</a>. With this feature, you can restrict its traffic by solely displaying ads to people who have already visited your site. Since they already know who you are and have shown an interested in your offerings, they‚Äôre more likely to be further along in the purchase cycle and ready to convert than your standard audience.</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="2bfffde5-83f7-4c8b-94a9-a7151800c4e0" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/adwords-tips-rlsa-1.jpg" alt="rlsa target and bid settings" width="639" height="372" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p>If you decide to go this route, it crucial that you execute it properly. With RLSA, your primary targeting criteria is still keywords‚Äîyour remarketing list is then layered in as a secondary targeting method. When adding your remarketing list, you have the opportunity to set it to ‚Äúbid only‚Äù or ‚Äútarget and bid.‚Äù In this scenario, be sure to select ‚Äútarget and bid‚Äù, which limits your ads‚Äô visibility to past site visitors.</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2016/07/18/actionable-adwords-tips">4 Super-Actionable Google Ads Tips to Try Right Now</a> appeared first on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com">WordStream</a>.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
