		<item>
		<title>Wow-Facebook Ads on 3rd Party Sites for Non-Users</title>
		<link>https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2016/06/01/facebook-ads-for-non-users</link>
					<comments>https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2016/06/01/facebook-ads-for-non-users#respond</comments>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Erin Sagin]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Wed, 01 Jun 2016 05:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Facebook Ads]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Social Media]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2016/06/01/facebook-ads-for-non-users/</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[<p>Facebook is finally extending its reach into uncharted territory--it's serving ads to non-users on third party sites. Learn exactly how this change will work.</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2016/06/01/facebook-ads-for-non-users">Wow-Facebook Ads on 3rd Party Sites for Non-Users</a> appeared first on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com">WordStream</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>This is my mom.</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="afa751dc-4e26-4e5c-a045-7154cda91853" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/facebook-news-mom.png" alt="my mom!" width="268" height="254" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>She is many advertisers‚Äô dream girl. She‚Äôs a full-time housewife, armed with a healthy wallet and plenty of time to peruse the internet. Moreover, she lovingly serves as a part-time personal assistant for most of my immediate family‚Äîmeaning that she‚Äôs perpetually online shopping for everything ranging from household supplies to clothes for my dad to flights for us kids.</p>
<p>She fits the perfect profile for so many online advertisers and yet, for years, she‚Äôs eluded many of their ads. Why? Because this woman is staunchly anti-Facebook. She thinks it‚Äôs creepy and invasive, and despite lots of prodding from me and my siblings, she‚Äôs held strong and has yet to set up a profile.</p>
<p><a href="/blog/ws/2015/05/04/future-of-online-advertising">Identity-based targeting</a> is one of the hottest (and most powerful) tactics in digital marketing today. Social media platforms have rich personal data and sophisticated methods to categorize their users, giving marketers the ability to connect with their most highly qualified prospects.</p>
<p>There‚Äôs one big downside to using this method: Advertisers are limited because they can only connect with social media users. And, while it certainly feels like everyone and their mom in on Facebook, I can quite literally attest that this is not quite the case.</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="e7b2a08f-17ed-48b1-85d6-411c1d7ddec5" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/facebook-news-demographics.png" alt="sprout social's facebook demographics infographic" width="641" height="670" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>As you can see from Sprout Social‚Äôs infographic on Facebook user demographics, my mom‚Äôs situation isn‚Äôt too rare. Only 56% of her peers (people ages 65+) have Facebook profiles.</p>
<p>Facebook recognized that this reality was troubling for advertisers focused on demographics with low Facebook adoption rates, so they‚Äôre finally taking action. That‚Äôs right, mom, there‚Äôs no more escaping <a href="/blog/ws/2015/12/14/how-to-create-facebook-ads">Facebook ads</a>!</p>
<p>The <a href="http://www.wsj.com/articles/facebook-wants-to-help-sell-every-ad-on-the-web-1464321603">news recently broke</a> that Facebook is extending its ad reach beyond Facebook users. For a year or so now, it‚Äôs been serving ads outside of the platform itself, through the Facebook Audience Network, a collection of third-party websites and mobile apps. However, these ads were only displayed to Facebook users, perusing these sites. <strong>Now, these ads will also be visible for non-users</strong>.</p>
<p>Here‚Äôs how the new process will work‚ÄîFacebook will leverage a combination of cookie tracking, plugins and button data to acquire data on non-Facebook users as they use the internet. This technique isn‚Äôt new‚Äîvarious online ad networks are already employing it‚Äîbut Facebook has a unique advantage, thanks to the vast amount of data it has on its own users‚Äô behavior. By linking the patterns in the non-users‚Äô behaviors to those of their existing users, it can get a more accurate depiction of the non-users‚Äô interests and demographics. As it starts to identify who these non-users are, it‚Äôll be able to include them in the Facebook Audience Network.</p>
<p>If all goes according to plan, this change will be hugely positive for <a href="/facebook-advertising">Facebook and Facebook advertisers</a> alike. Advertisers will be able to serve ads to even more qualified viewers and Facebook will reap even more dollars in ad revenue.</p>
<p>The only person who won‚Äôt be thrilled about this update? My beloved mother. But don‚Äôt worry¬†mom‚Äînon-users <em>will</em> have the ability to opt-out of these identity-based ads, should they wish.</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2016/06/01/facebook-ads-for-non-users">Wow-Facebook Ads on 3rd Party Sites for Non-Users</a> appeared first on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com">WordStream</a>.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
					<wfw:commentRss>https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2016/06/01/facebook-ads-for-non-users/feed</wfw:commentRss>
			<slash:comments>0</slash:comments>
		
		
			</item>
		<item>
		<title>Industry Reactions to the Big News from #GoogleSummit</title>
		<link>https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2016/06/01/industry-reactions-google-summit</link>
					<comments>https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2016/06/01/industry-reactions-google-summit#respond</comments>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Erin Sagin]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Wed, 01 Jun 2016 05:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Paid Search Marketing]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2016/06/01/industry-reactions-google-summit/</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[<p>The industry is abuzz with changes announced at this year's #GoogleSummit. See what the experts have to say about the updates.</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2016/06/01/industry-reactions-google-summit">Industry Reactions to the Big News from #GoogleSummit</a> appeared first on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com">WordStream</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>&nbsp;</p>
<section class="section">
<div class="section__inner section__inner--column_seperator">
<div class="column">
<div>
<h1>Industry Reactions to the Big News from #GoogleSummit</h1>
</div>
</div>
<div class="column">
<div></div>
</div>
<div class="column">
<div class="field-item">
<div class="text text--grey"><label class="label"><br />
Last updated: </label><br />
April 9, 2018</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="column">
<div>
<div class="tag">
<div class="tag__text">Paid Search Marketing</div>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="column">
<div>
<p>Every spring, the PPC community eagerly awaits the Google Performance Summit, where <a href="/blog/ws/2016/05/24/google-mobile-first">Google reveals new AdWords technologies</a> that they‚Äôll be releasing in the coming months. Last Tuesday was the big day and it definitely did not disappoint.</p>
<p>As I watched the livestream of the event, I was also tuned into Twitter‚Äôs #ppcchat to gauge industry leaders‚Äô reactions to the new Google products. The peanut gallery definitely kept things interesting‚Äîthey had plenty to say about the extravaganza, from poking fun at the Product Managers‚Äô corny skits to rejoicing over exciting new products to sharing their two cents on early-access beta performance.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="dad76a90-b895-499a-8cea-fc92d8dd20d7" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/industry-reactions-kirk.png" alt="kirk williams reaction" width="583" height="305" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p><a href="https://twitter.com/ppckirk"><em>@PPCKirk</em></a><em> managed to sum his feelings up in one tweet</em></p>
<p>Although there were mixed feelings for some new products, the overarching sentiment was positive. <a href="https://twitter.com/Realicity">James Svoboda</a> went as far as to say that this may have been the best Google Summit so far and I‚Äôm inclined to agree.</p>
<p>Here‚Äôs the scoop from the community on each of Google‚Äôs upcoming releases:</p>
<h2>Bidding by Device: 5 Stars and Cries of Hallelujah</h2>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="651f3038-399b-493d-9fd6-15862896451b" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/industry-reactions-tablets.png" alt="tablet bids" width="596" height="84" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Platform bidding is back and advertisers are beyond thrilled. In just a few months, we‚Äôll be able to set a base bid for one device time and then have the ability to set bid modifiers ranging from -100% to +900% for the other TWO devices. Meaning, you can set your base bids for mobile devices, set a modifier for tablets and then set a separate modifier for desktop searchers, ultimately giving advertisers more control.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="0195c094-8bd4-401c-be2f-2df0ab113542" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/industry-reactions-ecs.png" alt="enhanced campaigns frustrations" width="630" height="107" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p>Unsurprisingly, advertisers were thrilled to hear the news. Ever since Google shattered our hearts with the oh-so-controversial enhanced campaigns release, we‚Äôve been begging it give us back control of device-specific bids. We sent countless pleas to our account managers, petitioned AdWords through Twitter and consistently pushed the issue at partner summits. It‚Äôs heartening to see that the crew at Google took this feedback seriously and finally acquiesced to this request.</p>
<h2>Expanded Text Ads: 5 Stars, Coupled with a Loud Sigh</h2>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="4920902b-0511-4465-b05c-99c9fea7427b" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/industry-reactions-ads.png" alt="expanded ads" width="634" height="213" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>This is the biggest (literally, the <em>biggest</em>) change that‚Äôs happened to PPC ad copy in the history of AdWords. New, <a href="/blog/ws/2016/05/25/google-expanded-text-ads">expanded text ads</a> are <strong>50% larger</strong> than standard text ads and Google‚Äôs early studies show that they‚Äôre yielding CTR increases of up to 20%!</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="195aa4a8-fc38-4b5c-b9c5-1b543781314a" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/industry-reactions-expanded-ads.jpg" alt="expanded ads" width="800" height="274" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p>For years we‚Äôve been desperately cramming our messages into teensy tiny fields, praying they‚Äôll still make sense. The character counts limited creativity and made ad copy creation endlessly frustrating. As you can see in the example above, the new ads dwarf the old ones. They have two headlines that are 30 characters each, both description lines are 40 characters long, and the display URL now includes two, 15-character path fields. Having the freedom to craft higher-quality ad copy the way we <em>want</em> to, without having to adhere to super-short character fields is a pretty exciting prospect.</p>
<p>There‚Äôs just one downside‚Äîthese new ads will be a royal pain to create. We all know that overhauling ad copy for an entire account is challenging, to say the least. With this ad format, we‚Äôll have to create tons of new ads including more information than ever before. Even after you‚Äôve created an expanded alternative for all of your ad groups, you‚Äôll find yourself making adjustments rather frequently, as we start to discover new best practices for these lengthier ads. Le sigh.</p>
<p>The good news is that we‚Äôre already experimenting with expanded ads here at WordStream HQ. In the coming months, we‚Äôll be sharing our newfound tips and strategies to make updating these suckers less painful!</p>
<h2>Demographic Audiences for Search Ads: 4 Stars</h2>
<p>Demographic targeting on the search network is one of those <a href="/blog/ws/2015/02/25/bings-ads-vs-google-adwords">rare gems</a> that Bing Ads‚Äô has offered for years, but Google never seemed to want to adopt. In fact, it was one of those AdWords betas that we joked would never actually make it out of the beta program. Well my friends, it seems that that day has finally come and, as you can see from Mark‚Äôs tweet, we‚Äôre pretty exuberant about it.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="f4231dd8-d890-411b-8952-de142f42e34f" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/industry-reactions-demos.png" alt="demographic auds for search ads" width="633" height="107" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p>That said, there is some skepticism within the community with regards to the accuracy of Google‚Äôs demographic settings. It‚Äôll definitely be interesting to see how things pan out with this one‚Ä¶</p>
<h2>Similar Audiences for Search: 3.5 Stars and Some Healthy Skepticism</h2>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="c59d06cb-da3b-4f06-84eb-24b89be34c3d" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/industry-reactions-similar-aud.png" alt="similar audiences" width="571" height="336" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p>Clearly Larry Kim is pumped about this feature, and many advertisers fall into the same boat. We‚Äôre already accustomed to Similar Audiences, which gives us the ability to create lookalike audiences based off our GDN and Customer Match groups. Now, Google is officially extending this option to search audiences, too!</p>
<p>Feelings towards this new feature are mixed. Most industry peeps agree that it‚Äôs great in theory and, as the brilliant <a href="https://twitter.com/PPCKirk">Kirk Williams</a> pointed out, this could be hugely positive for SMBs, who don‚Äôt garner enough traffic to qualify for RLSA campaigns. However, many question whether Google can create lists that accurately reflect your ideal audience.</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="28712c06-3d93-48b8-91e9-0cbe9f452975" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/industry-reactions-skeptical.png" alt="skepticism for similar audiences" width="632" height="129" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>If Google can execute this the right way, it will be a major slam dunk for advertisers. But, until we‚Äôre able to test its effectiveness, the PPC jury‚Äôs out on Similar Audiences for Search.</p>
<h2>Updated AdWords UI: 3 Stars</h2>
<p>Google is promising a major overhaul of the AdWords UI, making it a more streamlined, intuitive platform for the end user. The philosophy behind the change is that AdWords should be more focused on the business it‚Äôs promoting, so account managers can optimize campaigns based on specific business goals and targets.</p>
<p>You can catch a sneak peek of the new, half-built interface <a href="/blog/ws/2016/05/25/new-adwords-interface">here</a>, but the key highlights are:</p>
<ul>
<li>Campaign creation wizards aimed at helping you determine exactly what type of campaigns and which settings will yield the best return for your business</li>
<li>A cleaner navigation system, with AdWords-generated opportunities available every step of the way</li>
<li>Newly designed dashboards to help users consume data more easily</li>
</ul>
<p>Personally, I think it‚Äôs high-time that Google updates the interface and I‚Äôm excited to see a more user-friendly design plan. This is great news for PPC beginners and those who aren‚Äôt super-involved with their accounts. That said, I understand why the industry pros‚Äô reactions to this update were lackluster.</p>
<p>First things first, many of us have spent ages getting comfortable with the existing interface. Now that we know it like the back of our hands, Google‚Äôs switching things up and we have to learn a whole new setup?</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="ccc3e2c2-2da9-4273-a99d-9082a38ad8df" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/industry-reactions-ui.png" alt="new adwords ui" width="638" height="127" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p>On top of that, many are concerned that, as the AdWords team creates more streamlined workflows, they‚Äôll eliminate advanced options that provide advertisers with more control over their accounts.</p>
<p>Those with the greatest concerns are agencies. As AdWords becomes more prescriptive, will this eliminate the need for agencies? Will more businesses feel confident managing their campaigns in-house?</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="a7dc923b-244b-49d6-ad5c-953292b074e9" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/industry-reactions-new-ui.png" alt="new adwords ui reaction" width="665" height="86" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p>The good news is that the new UI isn‚Äôt hitting the net anytime soon. We‚Äôve got plenty of time to wrap our heads around these changes (and hopefully more sneak peeks) throughout the next few months.</p>
<p>Want to hear what others had to say about the Google Summit announcements? Check out these write-ups from my brilliant pals, <a href="http://www.ppchero.com/6-takeaways-from-googles-performance-summit/">Matt Umbro</a> and <a href="http://www.pointit.com/blog/google-summit-2016/">Maddie Cary</a>!</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="column">
<div class="views-element-container contextual-region"></div>
</div>
</div>
</section>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
